s=title> boat maintenance</span><hr size=1> Some things are unforseen, others are foreseeable. I want to share my experience so that others won't have to find themselves in our position; unable to make good in storm conditions. <br>
<br>
 After another stormy experience on the Great Salt Lake, this time requiring rescue, though with reluctance and wounded pride, another lesson was learned. This time it is about diligence in maintaining the smallest details on a boat to keep her sailing well and able bodied to bring a crew in under storm conditions. Though there are times when everything can not be known, and bad luck plays a part.<br>
<br>
Our Capri 30 proved herself worthy again, in a storm. Her crew, did too. Our first problem became the outboard motor. She began to fail. Extra spark plugs were on board and exchange on the motor. However, this seemed not to be the problem. The water cooling system was not functioning and the engine would overheat. This rendered us without a motor. We were unable to check and repair this system on the boat. Most likely she was overworked and underpaid. This same motor helped us motor a great distance on the 80 miler during extreme storm conditions. She was just too tired too perform once again. Lesson one: after extensive use of a motor, pull her off the boat and have her tended to. Treat her like a lady. Treat her well.<br>
<br>
Next came the ripping of a main from a reef point gromet in the middle of the sail. We had reefed the main in anticipation of strong winds. Sure enough the winds came and we were glad for the reef. Without warning, a small piece of hardware broke off, most likely a toggle, from the reef line aft on the main. This sent the aft portion of the main out and the point were the extra sail was secured from a gromet and around the boom, ripped through the main under this extra pressure. No main to help us power forward. Small detail that perhaps could have been forseen by monitoring the hardware. All the little things which seem unimportant, became very important in an instant. Perhaps, it couldn't have been expected, but as a sailor, every detail is reviewed. On the water in a storm, minute changes make a difference. <br>
<br>
No main, no motor and a long way to go southward, directly into a south storm. It took a very long time to make good on distance with only a 110% genoa. Crew fatigue plays a part. Perhaps it was the lilt in my voice over the VHF when I explained to the folks at the marina that once again, we bare-poled our boat and were waiting out another storm, lightening and darkness from East, West and then North. In the dark it was difficult to determine where these storms were going to go and what they would do. We took the waves and th wind. It was with great relief that Resuce 1 from the South shore came and towed us in. We could have made it on our own, but looking back, the crew was getting weaker, and a weak crew puts everyone at risk. Sea sickness came over one member. The skipper listened to another crew member and knew that when one is in fear of the situation, listen to the one and seek reassurance for them, be that a life jacket or rescue. <br>
<br>
Enough can't be said about the &quot;rescuers&quot;. They were direct and calm in the rescue. Much needed help. Thank you, thank you, thank you.<br>
<br>
Check your boat for it's working order. Hopefully it will pay off. Take a crew that is well rested on any of your journeys. You may need them to give you 110%. Ours did.<br>
